<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="100" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1884,2020]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,153,575]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="100" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,1884,1911]" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
East Asian species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curtis" authorityYear="1833" box="[648,744,1885,1911]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[648,744,1885,1911]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Loricula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are recognized primarily by: Moderate to large size (1.5â3.0 mm in total length but females much shorter than 2.4â3.0 mm in macropterous males); basic coloration brownish, partly or sometimes largely reddish; always sexually dimorphic; male adult always macropterous whereas female rounded, either coleopteroid (
<figureCitation box="[490,571,1993,2019]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1892,1917]" captionTargetBox="[162,1393,610,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,597,1867]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus images of Japanese Loricula species (adult females). AâC. L. mikawa sp. nov. (A: dorsal view, B: ventral view, C: right lateral view). D. L. miyamotoi Yasunaga &amp; Yamada, dorsal view. E. L. yakushima Yasunaga &amp; Yamada, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3736038" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3736038/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[586,623,1993,2019]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1650,1675]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,597,1622]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,597,1625]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Scanning electron micrographs for female of Loricula mikawa sp. nov. A. Dorsal habitus. B. Head, dorsal view. C. Anterior body, ventral view. D. Apex of labium, ventral view. E. Vestiture pattern on ventral surface of hemelytron. F. Scent efferent system. G. Protarsus and grooming comb. H. Mestatarsus. I. Apex of abdomen, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3736040" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3736040/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">3A</figureCitation>
), micropterous (
<figureCitation box="[811,901,1993,2019]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1643,1668]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,237,1614]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,237,1618]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron micrographs for Japanese Loricula species (adult females). AâC. L. mikawa sp. nov. DâF. L. miyamotoi. G, H. L. pilosella. I, J. L. yakushima. K, L. L. nikko. A, D, G, I &amp; K. Anterior body, dorsal view. B, E &amp; L. Ditto, left lateral view. C, F, H &amp; J. Posterolateral process of pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3736042" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3736042/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="99">Fig. 4K</figureCitation>
) or staphylinoidy; antennal segment II usually longer than IV; female pronotum trapezoid or campanulate, with more or less projected posterior angle (except for micropterous form with truncate pronotum); scent gland with narrow evaporative area (
<figureCitation box="[1160,1248,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1650,1675]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,597,1622]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,597,1625]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Scanning electron micrographs for female of Loricula mikawa sp. nov. A. Dorsal habitus. B. Head, dorsal view. C. Anterior body, ventral view. D. Apex of labium, ventral view. E. Vestiture pattern on ventral surface of hemelytron. F. Scent efferent system. G. Protarsus and grooming comb. H. Mestatarsus. I. Apex of abdomen, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3736040" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3736040/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
); male forewing membrane with corial process (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K." box="[540,847,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" pagination="1209 - 1227" refId="ref4104" refString="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K. (2017) Review of the microphysid genus Loricula Curtis in Japan (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Microphysidae), with descriptions of three new species. Journal of Natural History, 51, 1209 - 1227. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222933.2017.1324053" type="journal article" year="2017">Yasunaga &amp; Yamada, 2017</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Maehara, S. &amp; Ishikawa, T. &amp; Takai, M." box="[858,1097,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" refId="ref4161" refString="Yasunaga, T., Maehara, S., Ishikawa, T. &amp; Takai, M. (2018) Guidebook to the heteropteran world- Basic ecology, morphology, classification and research methodology. Zenkoku Noson Kyoiku Kyokai Publ. Co. Ltd., Tokyo, 212 pp. [in Japanese]" type="book" year="2018">
Yasunaga 
<emphasis box="[973,1022,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">et al</emphasis>
. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
); and male parameres more or less asymmetrical. Further diagnostic characters were provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K." box="[899,1217,261,287]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" pagination="1209 - 1227" refId="ref4104" refString="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K. (2017) Review of the microphysid genus Loricula Curtis in Japan (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Microphysidae), with descriptions of three new species. Journal of Natural History, 51, 1209 - 1227. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222933.2017.1324053" type="journal article" year="2017">Yasunaga &amp; Yamada (2017)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="100" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,153,575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,296,323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">Distribution.</emphasis>
Palearctic and Nearctic regions (mostly temperate and cold temperate climate zones; Nearctic populations are considered to have been introduced) (
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K." box="[750,1053,333,359]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" pagination="1209 - 1227" refId="ref4104" refString="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K. (2017) Review of the microphysid genus Loricula Curtis in Japan (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Microphysidae), with descriptions of three new species. Journal of Natural History, 51, 1209 - 1227. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222933.2017.1324053" type="journal article" year="2017">Yasunaga &amp; Yamada 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="101" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,153,575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,368,395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curtis" authorityYear="1833" box="[339,435,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[339,435,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">Loricula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are dominantly recorded from the western Palearctic Region (
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K." pageId="2" pageNumber="100" pagination="1209 - 1227" refId="ref4104" refString="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K. (2017) Review of the microphysid genus Loricula Curtis in Japan (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Microphysidae), with descriptions of three new species. Journal of Natural History, 51, 1209 - 1227. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222933.2017.1324053" type="journal article" year="2017">Yasunaga &amp; Yamada, 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Because of its tiny size, restricted distribution and obscure habits, this genus has hardly been studied. The male adults resemble anthocorids, whereas the females have remarkable wing polymorphism. Following a category of heteropteran wing forms suggested by Henry (2012) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Slater, J. A." box="[839,1099,476,503]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" refId="ref3990" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Slater, J. A. (1995) True bugs of the world (Hemiptera: Heteroptera). Classification and natural history. Cornell University Press, Ithaca and London, xii + 337 pp." type="book" year="1995">Schuh &amp; Slater (1995)</bibRefCitation>
, most of the female adults of Japanese 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curtis" authorityYear="1833" box="[256,352,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[256,352,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">Loricula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are coleopteroid (only 
<taxonomicName box="[696,785,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nikko">
<emphasis box="[696,785,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">L. nikko</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is micropterous). In 
<collectingCountry box="[1014,1081,513,539]" name="Japan" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">Japan</collectingCountry>
, five congeners are now known. However, two species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Yasunaga &amp; Yamada &amp; Ohno, 2020" authorityName="Yasunaga &amp; Yamada &amp; Ohno" authorityYear="2020" box="[411,527,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mikawa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[411,527,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">L. mikawa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[534,624,549,575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[534,624,549,575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[678,769,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nikko">
<emphasis box="[678,769,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="100">L. nikko</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are currently represented only by females.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3736038" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3736038" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3736038/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="100" startId="2.[151,250,1892,1917]" targetBox="[162,1393,610,1854]" targetPageId="2">
