<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,575]" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">
As suggested by 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K." box="[396,721,153,179]" pageId="3" pageNumber="101" pagination="1209 - 1227" refId="ref4104" refString="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K. (2017) Review of the microphysid genus Loricula Curtis in Japan (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Microphysidae), with descriptions of three new species. Journal of Natural History, 51, 1209 - 1227. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222933.2017.1324053" type="journal article" year="2017">Yasunaga &amp; Yamada (2017)</bibRefCitation>
, the females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curtis" authorityYear="1833" box="[908,1004,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[908,1004,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">Loricula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species appear to complete its whole life cycle in the litter at the forest floor and, therefore, it is usually difficult to collect the female specimens in good number. The females were observed to crawl up on the low vegetation (mostly ferns, cf. 
<figureCitation box="[1147,1234,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1742,1767]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,689,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,689,1717]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitat (A, B) and habitus image of female adult (C) for Loricula mikawa sp. nov. (AâC) and L. miyamotoi Yasunaga &amp; Yamada (D). A &amp; B. Secondary evergreen broadleaf forest in Toyoda City where L. mikawa occurs. C. L. mikawa, female. D. Well-preserved deciduous forest, habitat of L. miyamotoi (Yamanashi Prefecture, Japan). D: Image courtesy of T. Ishikawa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3736036" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3736036/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
), mossy stones or fungous rotten logs probably for contact with the males during a limited breeding season (from June to July in 
<collectingCountry box="[1372,1436,261,287]" name="Japan" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">Japan</collectingCountry>
mainland). Incidentally, the female adults of 
<taxonomicName authority="Yasunaga &amp; Yamada &amp; Ohno, 2020" authorityName="Yasunaga &amp; Yamada &amp; Ohno" authorityYear="2020" box="[653,770,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mikawa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[653,770,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">L. mikawa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[777,866,297,323]" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[777,866,297,323]" pageId="3" pageNumber="101" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
were found on tree trunks (
<figureCitation box="[1176,1261,297,323]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1742,1767]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,689,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,689,1717]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitat (A, B) and habitus image of female adult (C) for Loricula mikawa sp. nov. (AâC) and L. miyamotoi Yasunaga &amp; Yamada (D). A &amp; B. Secondary evergreen broadleaf forest in Toyoda City where L. mikawa occurs. C. L. mikawa, female. D. Well-preserved deciduous forest, habitat of L. miyamotoi (Yamanashi Prefecture, Japan). D: Image courtesy of T. Ishikawa." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3736036" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3736036/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
) at night.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,575]" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">
Careful observation using a tabletop SEM documented significant interspecific differences on the surface structures of the forewing (hemelytron) between four species (
<figureCitation box="[804,873,368,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1686,1711]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,633,1661]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,633,1661]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 5. Scanning electron micrographs for dorsal surface structure of female forewing (hemelytron). A. L. mikawa sp. nov. B. L. miyamotoi. C. L. pilosella. D. L. yakushima." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3736044" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3736044/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Variation in the pattern of granulate microstructures is noted for 
<taxonomicName box="[355,482,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosella">
<emphasis box="[355,482,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">L. pilosella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[541,692,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yakushima">
<emphasis box="[541,692,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">L. yakushima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
âdensely distributed, 
<taxonomicName box="[950,1100,406,431]" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miyamotoi">
<emphasis box="[950,1100,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">L. miyamotoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
âsparsely distributed, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Yasunaga &amp; Yamada &amp; Ohno, 2020" authorityName="Yasunaga &amp; Yamada &amp; Ohno" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Microphysidae" genus="Loricula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mikawa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">L. mikawa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[245,335,441,467]" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[245,335,441,467]" pageId="3" pageNumber="101" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
âabsent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,575]" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">
Although little is known about biology and immature forms of microphysid bugs, the eggs are remarkably large-sized as in 
<figureCitation box="[341,418,513,539]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1940,1965]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,309,1915]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,309,1915]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Compound microscopic images showing detailed morphology for L. mikawa sp. nov., female. A. Head and pronotum, dorsal view. B. Antenna. C. Labium. D. Thorax, ventral surface. E. Forewing base. F. Abdomen, ventral view. G. Apodemal process. H. Genital segments, ventral view. I. Three eggs found in abdomen (F)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3736046" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3736046/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">Fig. 6I</figureCitation>
, comparing with those of other heteropterans (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K." box="[982,1289,513,539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="101" pagination="1209 - 1227" refId="ref4104" refString="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Yamada, K. (2017) Review of the microphysid genus Loricula Curtis in Japan (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Microphysidae), with descriptions of three new species. Journal of Natural History, 51, 1209 - 1227. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222933.2017.1324053" type="journal article" year="2017">Yasunaga &amp; Yamada, 2017</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Maehara, S. &amp; Ishikawa, T. &amp; Takai, M." pageId="3" pageNumber="101" refId="ref4161" refString="Yasunaga, T., Maehara, S., Ishikawa, T. &amp; Takai, M. (2018) Guidebook to the heteropteran world- Basic ecology, morphology, classification and research methodology. Zenkoku Noson Kyoiku Kyokai Publ. Co. Ltd., Tokyo, 212 pp. [in Japanese]" type="book" year="2018">
Yasunaga 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="101">et al</emphasis>
., 2018
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
